author: Robin Ahmed
title: WWE Trademarks New John Cena Farewell Tour Gear for Fans
text:
John Cena is creating a lot of excitement in the WWE community after announcing he will enter the Royal Rumble in February. The hype is already high, as shown by the ticket sales for the big event.
Fans are wondering if Cena might win the 30-man Rumble match, and WWE is using this excitement to boost their business. Recently, reports say that new John Cena merchandise, as part of his farewell tour, will be released soon.
Reports say that WWE has trademarked new merchandise for John Cena’s farewell tour. The merchandise includes clothing, collectibles, and other items to remember his last matches. The list includes:
WWE had filed a trademark application for the term 'Cenation'. pic.twitter.com/IYpZQSx0Sd
— Wrestle Features (@WrestleFeatures) January 16, 2025 Trading cards, collector albums, stickers, and framed photos Posters, calendars, decals, and party supplies Comic books, picture books, coloring books, and souvenir programs Paper napkins, table linens, greeting cards, and wrapping paper WWE’s decision to create this special merchandise shows how important Cena’s retirement tour is and how a big draw he still is in wrestling.
John Cena drops big hint about WrestleMania 41 Reports say this year’s WrestleMania might be John Cena’s last. But no one knows who he’ll face at the big event. However, during Raw’s Netflix debut, the 16-time champ named some possible opponents for his final match, even though he admitted that winning his 17th title might never happen.
John Cena, a WWE legend for over 20 years, mentioned CM Punk, Logan Paul, Gunther, and Cody Rhodes as possible rivals. He also hinted he might not break the record for most world championships.
The first of many beautiful John Cena promos this year ❤️ #RAWOnNetflix pic.twitter.com/sXvuHKq8zG
— The Movement – Pro Wrestling (@TheMovementXx) January 7, 2025 Cena hasn’t won a singles match in over 2,000 days, preparing for one last big underdog story. He aims to win the 30-man battle royal for the third time, tying Stone Cold Steve Austin’s record.
